USA: Repeating is the Mother of Wisdom
It is comical, with which schoolboy effort Barack Obama, the president with the reputation of the smartest, repeats on the Afghan question the strategy of his predecessor, whom he himself considered to be the stupidest.
When he finally sweated out his eagerly anticipated Afghan doctrine, it turned out that he copied it through a copycat from Bush’s Iraq script three years ago.
Not only does he use "as in Iraq" several times in the text itself, but he did not hesitate to use the name Bush's statement of January 2007 as the name of his own declaration: "A new way forward".
Three years ago, he himself criticized Bush's idea of sending fresh military reinforcements to Iraq plagued by civil war as "unresponsible and disastrous decisions in his wake."
However, the following months have shown that Bush’s strategy based on the recommendations of field commanders was the only possible and very successful one so far that there is no discussion of Iraq at all in news events today.
It did not improve Bush’s reputation, but he objectively left his successor with a much more grateful starting point than expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama hopes that the miracle will repeat itself.
He was asked to increase his military contingent once again by field commanders, in particular Chief of the Afghan operation General Stanley McCristal, who, despite subordinating practices, harshly criticized hesitant shooters in the White House.
He asked 40,000 men to break the situation for the better.
The president hesitated for three months, but he didn't get any better, so at least he cheated the general out of 10,000 soldiers.
From Europe he managed to squeeze out the promise of another 5,000, even though he originally counted on at least 10.
The most problematic thing about Obama’s entire strategy seems to be his intention to start withdrawing troops from Afghanistan in 18 months and to end this process within three years. Obama’s whole doctrine raises more questions than it provides answers.
Many doubt that half the increase will yield the same fruit as the advance in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars of recent years, Iraqi society is relatively well organized, its leaders honor agreements.
The Afghan situation is marked by the opposite symptom - no one can be relied on and no agreements are observed.
Under these conditions, Afghan security forces used to change masters every day are badly prepared, depending on how convenient it is for them.
Political institutions, even if formally established, will remain just a potemkin village for which patriarchal tribal relations will continue to flourish.
Balancing the interests of various ethnic groups is extremely difficult given the ambiguity of conditions that make Pakistani and Iranian influences even more difficult.
Even building an "actable state", which is the minimalist objective of the entire operation, does not seem too real.
The time horizon of Obama’s strategy is striking with its voluntarism.
The situation in Afghanistan has only been deteriorating over the past eight years and is now on the verge of an explosion.
To believe that soldiers sent to war for the purpose of "early return home" will produce a miracle here, only the soul can truly romantic, truly untouched.
Politically speaking, setting the date of military withdrawal is purely irresponsible, as the Taliban will see this as an indirect confession of American defeat.
The latest NATO summit has shown that Europeans’ willingness to participate in combat operations in Afghanistan is going to be reduced.
European politicians do not know and do not want to explain to their voters how the safety of Germany or Italy is related to the war in the foothills of Hindukush.
Another factor able to intervene radically is the development of events around Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the strengthened sanctions do not affect the Iranians, a difficult question will arise before the United States as to whether or not to try to solve the problem by military force.
It will need to be answered at a time when Obama says America will move on to winning withdrawals from Afghanistan.
However, any such solution will also mean a dramatic turn in the Afghan situation.
The only Band-Aid for Barack Obama is the fact that there are three years left until the presidential election, and therefore there is enough time left to come up with another strategy if this one turns out to be a total failure.
