Czech discovery: a substance that also works on 'solid' HIV viruses
A team of Czech and German scientists are testing new compounds that can slow the spread of HIV in the body.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also works on viruses that have already gained immunity from drugs.
This fact in some cases outweighs the fact that the compound does not act as strongly on a common variant of the virus as some medicines already available.
AIDS disease cannot be cured yet.
However, patients may have a significant life extension of a mixture of medicines that prevent HIV from multiplying in the body.
However, their use is accompanied by a number of side effects.
In addition, incomplete suppression of virus reproduction results in the development of so-called resistant viruses against which drugs are no longer effective.
The work of experts from the three institutes of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, VŠCHT Prague and the University of Heidelberg opens the way to deal with resistance of the virus.
They have shown that a substance called metal carboranes acts on the protein responsible for the multiplication of the HIV virus.
Metalocarbons are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus differently than any medicine currently in use, so they can overcome the problem of resistance.
In their work, scientists come up with new ‘improved’ compounds prepared on the basis of their molecular mechanism of binding to viral protein.
Metalocarborans have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multiwalled cages made up of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms are connected by the metal atom, in this case by cobalt.
A treacherous and resistant virus
HIV protease is a protein of the HIV virus that is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without HIV protease caused by HIV virus fission, mature infectious virus particles would not have been produced.
When we stop HIV protease, we stop the spread of the virus in the patient's body, scientists explain in a press release published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic.
In a paper published in the Journal of Medical Chemistry, scientists describe a series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see table) are linked by a short organic chain that is further systematically modified.
A little weaker, but more reliable.
The effect of this series of anti-HIV protease substances has been tested in the test tube and also against its resistant (resistant) variants obtained from patients infected with HIV.
The effect of metal-carborans on the normal variant of the enzyme is not as strong as with clinically used drugs, but it does not lose its effect on resistant variants against which the drugs used are often ineffective.
