Michael Zammit Cutajar, who designed a six-page document, crumpled from 180 pages of the text from the meeting to focus on what a top climate official at the UN, Yvo de Boer, described as a "big picture".
It outlines outlines for a possible agreement in which industrial nations could jointly limit their emissions to 25 to 45 percent in comparison with 1990 levels, while major developing countries could reduce their emissions to 15 to 30 percent during this period.
Together, countries would reduce emissions by 2050 between 50 and 95 percent.
