Turkey’s justice has dissolved for the Kurdish party, and this decision has had serious consequences.
The Turkish Constitutional Court decided on Friday to abolish the main Pro-Kurd party in the country. This decision immediately triggered protest demonstrations in the Kurdish community in the south-east of the country and in Istanbul.
This decision can greatly complicate the task of the government, which is trying to give the Kurdish community a friendly hand and thus try to end 25 years of conflict.
The Democratic Society Party (DTP) was dissolved because it became "a nest of activities threatening the independence of the state and its indivisible unity," said Hasim Kilic, Chairman of the Supreme Court, after four days of negotiations.
The decision was adopted unanimously by 11 judges, when a majority of seven votes were needed to disband the party, Kiliç said, adding that 37 party cadres, including its President Ahmet Türk and Member Aysela Tugluk, were banned from participating in political life for five years.
At the same time, the judge announced the abolition of the parliamentary immunity enjoyed by Mr Türk and Mrs Tugluk and the confiscation of the Party's assets by the Ministry of Finance.
The DTP has 21 seats in Parliament (of 500).
The Party's leadership has already pointed out before the verdict that Members would rather leave Parliament than appear in it as non-political Members.
The decision is a continuation of the process initiated in 2007 by Prosecutor of the Court of Cassation Abdurrahman Yalcinkay, who accuses DTP of obedience to the "commands" of the Working Party of Kurdistan (PKK), which Ankara and many countries consider to be a terrorist organisation.
Many observers believe that DTP is the legal political showcase of the PKK rebels.
The party assures that it has no "basic link" with the PKK, but refuses to call it a terrorist organization and calls on the government to negotiate with it.
The verdict of the court comes at a time when the government is giving the Kurdish community a friendly hand and offering a number of measures to strengthen their rights and trying to limit the support of the Kurds against the PKK to end the conflict.
The DTP management has confirmed that the dissolution of the party could lead to the resumption of tensions in the southeast of Anatolia, where in recent weeks many demonstrations have turned against the conditions under which the PKK leader Abdullah Öcalan is being held in conflict with the police.
Since the announcement of the decision of justice, thousands of demonstrators have gathered before the DTP headquarters in Diyarbakir, a large city in the southeast, mainly inhabited by the Kurds.
Police used tear grenades and water cannons, protestors threw Molotov cocktails again or shot stones from slingshots.
Also in Istanbul, about 100 people demonstrated.
After the verdict was delivered, Mr Türk said that justice's decision would only "enhance despair".
Turkey cannot solve this question by banning the party, said in the press.
The government, formed by a party formed from the Islamist movement, also condemned this decision.
We're on principle against the interference of the parties.
It doesn't solve anything, Minister of Energy Taner Yildiz said.
This decision is a total blast of the democratic proposals launched by the government, commented political scientist Ahmet Insel.
Of course we can look forward to the reaction from PKK, added.
