Tawa hallae looked like a lot of other carnivorous dinosaurs: An animal two metres long and 1.50 metres high ran on two strong hind limbs, had an oblong skull with sharp, curved teeth, short front limbs with sickle claws and a long tail.
If this species lived a few million years later, there would be nothing special.
Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas, Austin, and colleagues in the Thursday edition of Science magazine write that Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs with these physical characteristics.
The animal lived about 215 million years ago in today’s New Mexico, which was then in the equatorial dry area of the Pangea supercontinent.
Tawa opens a new window to the earlier evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
It shows us a lot about kinship, expansion and signs of early dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other paleontologists began excavating in Ghost Ranch, north of New Mexico.
Sometimes in one day we found a dozen dinosaur bones, which is unprecedented for Triassic sediments, reports a member of the Randall Irmis team from the Museum of Natural History in Utah.
Some of the bones were quickly identified by scientists as a new species.
During the excavation, they collected the remains from a total of five individuals.
The discovery confirms the theory of the early history of dinosaurs.
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of Hopi Indians.
For Sterling Nesbitt, this is an unusual find: "The photos of dinosaurs from the Triassic are very rare, mostly they only find individual fragments."
Other dinosaur experts do not share this enthusiasm without reservation.
Especially sensational this finding is not, but confirms some theories about the early history of dinosaurs, says perhaps Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
In the current scientific opinion, dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
