75% of working mothers have mother-related work problems.
Discrimination in employment has increased in recent years, especially among women of younger years who intend to have a child.
This is the result of the study 'Plodence and career of Spanish women' carried out by CSIC in cooperation with the Institute of Women.
The study was attended by 9.737 women aged between 15 and 75 years and results are clear: 75% of working mothers have limited opportunities in the labour market due to maternity.
The study points out that at the beginning of the partnership there are many differences in the opinion of the number of children according to whether they work or not and also according to the type of employment.
Women who do not work outside the home, work part-time or do not have stable jobs, start living with a partner earlier, give birth to the first child before, and generally have more children.
On the other hand, women with stable employment, especially in the public sector, partner coexistence and motherhood, postpone and have fewer offspring.
"Women from 35 to 49 years of age with stable employment have the first child on average 3.7 years from the beginning of cohabitation with a partner. This figure is 4.1 in the case of women who have devoted more of their lives to achieving stable employment and have therefore had to postpone the cohabitation and arrival of children.
The type of profession also has a strong influence on motherhood, although less impact on the time of starting cohabitation with a partner", explains Margarita Delgado, who is involved in research in CSIC.
Another factor affecting women’s age at the time of marriage and birth is the degree of education.
Research shows that the higher the degree of education, the higher the age when women get married and have their first child.
The differences are also among women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35- to 49-year-old group, women with basic and higher education gave birth to their first child at the age of 25,1 or 32.1 respectively.
"There is another difference between women depending on their degree of education.
Women with basic education are getting married and giving birth to the first child before they find stable employment, while women with medium or high education are taking the opposite step towards getting a stable job, rather than getting married and giving birth to the first child," says Delgado.
