The auxiliary system for the hand brake is already mandatory equipment.
As with the ABS anti-lock system, it will also be with the stability control of the ESP, the auxiliary handbrake systems, all of which will become compulsory equipment for European cars.
In fact, it already forms part of the mandatory equipment of all newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for others, a deadline is set to address the shortage, which is February 2011.
The measures introduced in the EU aim to increase the protection of pedestrians, and it works by helping to prevent many collisions.
The auxiliary hand brake system increases the pressure on the brakes in the emergency case, which the system finds out when the driver steps down.
But it's not always able to hold this pressure to the end.
According to a study carried out by Bosch auto parts manufacturer, a third of the drivers who are in an accident did not hit the brake before the crash, and half of them did not use the brake to the full.
Up to 1.100 accidents
On the other hand, this assistance requires maximum speed from the braking system, reducing the braking distance of the vehicle.
According to a study conducted in the EU itself, if all vehicles were equipped with this type of equipment, up to 1 100 fatal pedestrian-related accidents per year could be avoided.
The reduction of this number will be even more marked-according to calculations would prevent one of the four accidents affecting persons-after the introduction of so-called intelligent handbrake systems.
In this case, vehicles will be equipped with a system (with radar or camera) to detect obstacles and report them to the driver, except for light braking.
If the driver responds, he will be helped to increase the pressure on the pedal if needed.
